{"key":"post-27928665","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>27928665</id>\n<content>It's best to always test a new drum sterilizer with an air compressor before using steam.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It's also best to never exceed 1 to at most 2 psi.&amp;nbsp; As said above, you've created a bomb by having a sealed drum.&amp;nbsp; Remember, when water turns to steam, it expands by a factor of at least 1600 at atmospheric pressure.&amp;nbsp; Add some pressure and it's even greater if a rip occurs in the drum.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I'd open up that relief valve so it's always open during use. This will allow steam to constantly escape.&amp;nbsp; Adjust the burner so only a small amount escapes after the first hour or so.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>27928686</next>\n<prev>27928660</prev>\n<first>27927928</first>\n<last>27984905</last>\n<when>1662041346</when>\n<utime>09/01/22 05:09 PM</utime>\n</post>"}